Diagnosis. Maximum known TL 695 mm (
Taylor, 1968
). PA 83–102 . SG absent. Head slightly compressed ventrally, narrower than most of body. Eye in open orbit, visible or not under skin. Small anterior tentacles, below nostrils, near margin of mouth, much closer to nostrils than corner of mouth, not visible from above. Nostrils subtriangular, visible or not from above. Body laterally compressed. A dorsal keel or fin, at least on posterior half of body. Marked sexual dimorphism in terminal region, females having narrower and more pointed terminus. Vent disk elongate anteriorly, rounded posteriorly, may or may not be depressed, surrounded by fleshy folds of skin in both sexes. Paired anal papillae present or absent. Dermal and subdermal scales absent. Tongue anteriorly completely attached to mandibular mucosa; two large narial plugs. Four series of teeth, all monocuspid.
